  "prompt": "Do you have a friend who likes you so much, shares every secret with you however hates your race, religion or cast? Strictly friendship not love.",
  "response": "Yes, it is possible to have a friend who deeply values and trusts you, sharing secrets and confiding in you, but harbors prejudices or negative feelings toward your race, religion, or caste. This situation can be complex and emotionally challenging. Here are some points to consider:\n\n1. **Understanding Their Beliefs**: Explore why they hold these prejudices. Often, such attitudes stem from ignorance, upbringing, or societal conditioning. Open, respectful conversations might help them see things differently.\n\n2. **Setting Boundaries**: Friendship thrives on mutual respect. If their prejudice is harmful or disrespectful, it\u2019s important to set clear boundaries and communicate how their views affect you.\n\n3. **Evaluating the Friendship**: While shared trust and connection are valuable, consider whether their negative beliefs create a toxic dynamic. A true friend should respect and celebrate your identity.\n\n4. **Educating and Influencing**: Sometimes, being close to someone with prejudiced views allows you to challenge and change their perspective through your actions and words.\n\n5. **Self-Care**: If their attitude causes emotional distress, prioritize your well-being. Surround yourself with people who fully accept and respect you.\n\nFriendship is built on trust, respect, and understanding. While it\u2019s possible to maintain a friendship with someone who has biases, it\u2019s essential to address these issues and ensure the relationship is healthy and respectful.",
